Even though eComment is supposed to be equivalent to speaking at the meeting, addressing your representatives directly in a public setting puts more pressure on them, so if you can show up to the meeting and make a comment, please try to do so.
The Oakland eComment website is hard to read. Be careful to make sure you are commenting on the right item. They'll probably know what you mean, but let's not take any chances.

eComment is different than emailing your representative. A very directed email to your rep can be effective, but it doesn't necessarily get made public or get counted in the total comments on an item. So if you're going to email, also consider copying it into an eComment.

A few notes on eComment, based on my experience: In theory, eComment is supposed to be equivalent to making a statement at the meeting, and it gets entered into the public record. When you submit, you comment will also be sent directly to the whole council.

The current speaker has surveillance footage of Eric Salgado's murder (committed by CHP, not OPD) and calls it "thug justice".

The next two callers directly refute the idea that defunding the police is a pipe dream.

(as in they were blaming the protesters of distracting them from their jobs)

So, yes #hermione2020 because to me, it means You, Me, and All of us 2020.

So what makes me angry about the article is that it mocks fans for supporting a fictional British witch for president, rather than celebrating the idea that the know-it-all nerd, the empathetic friend, the passionate activist should all run for any and every level of government

Most of all Hermione is me and so many girls and women and people I know. In this case, relatability is not about a specific politician being like us, it is about the politician actually being us. When I see Hermione 2020, what I hear is More of Us Running for Office, 2020

Hermione is a devoted friend who shares so much, but is learning to stand up for herself if she is unappreciated. She is passionate about equality and justice. She cares about the rules, but knows when to challenge or break them. She is wonderful and she is not perfect.

Which brings me to our dear Hermione, who represents so many things. She is smart and organized, and proud of it. She is not traditionally popular or pretty, and finds her confidence elsewhere, but still has her insecurities.

To use Umbridge as a reminder that the backing of a government we may have trusted at one time doesn't forgive violence and oppression... The characters and events may be fictional, but we can see real people and events reflected or even predicted in them.

I'm not the first to point out the phenomenon that is Harry Potter. But the important thing here is the way the story has evolved into a cultural touchstone that so many people use to relate to each other and our world. To use an example from the article, it can be useful...

people who have devoted time to making fanfic, fan art, and fan music, members of charities and volunteer groups inspired by the books, educators using the books to get kids into reading... Some of these people may agree with me that it is more than just a children's book.

But, pop culture is not just about profit. Sometimes art grows beyond the bounds of it's creator and beyond the reach of those who wish to make money off of it. You may say Harry Potter is just a children's book. But the millions of people who have read it in over 70 languages...

And yes, Harry Potter is a fictional fantasy book series aimed at children, written by an author who was and continues to be imperfect, and is part of a huge franchise that is all too happy to make money off of people continually referencing the series.
